1
00:01:48,234 --> 00:01:50,153
<i>You got any stories, friend?</i>

2
00:01:53,698 --> 00:01:56,701
Yeah, I suppose I do.

3
00:01:59,954 --> 00:02:02,499
You want to know
the saddest thing I ever saw?

4
00:02:03,291 --> 00:02:06,836
When I was a boy,
my brother and I wanted a dog.

5
00:02:07,629 --> 00:02:11,424
So, our father took in an old greyhound.

6
00:02:12,550 --> 00:02:14,594
- Never seen a greyhound, have you?
- No.

7
00:02:15,303 --> 00:02:17,972
Seen a few showdowns in my day.

8
00:02:21,017 --> 00:02:23,436
A greyhound is a racing dog.

9
00:02:23,686 --> 00:02:25,647
It spends its life running in circles,

10
00:02:26,272 --> 00:02:29,609
chasing a bit of felt
made up like a rabbit.

11
00:02:30,401 --> 00:02:32,821
One day, we took it to the park.

12
00:02:33,696 --> 00:02:36,783
Now, Dad had warned us
how fast that dog was,

13
00:02:37,116 --> 00:02:38,952
but we couldn't resist.

14
00:02:39,160 --> 00:02:41,120
So, my brother took off the leash.

15
00:02:41,371 --> 00:02:46,584
And in that instant,
the dog spotted a cat.

16
00:02:47,001 --> 00:02:49,963
I imagine it must have looked
just like that piece of felt.

17
00:02:51,965 --> 00:02:53,258
He ran.

18
00:02:55,510 --> 00:03:02,225
Never saw a thing as beautiful
as that old dog running.

19
00:03:04,477 --> 00:03:07,522
<i>Until at last, he finally caught it.</i>

20
00:03:09,023 --> 00:03:13,570
And to the horror of everyone,
he killed that little cat.

21
00:03:13,862 --> 00:03:15,822
Tore it to pieces.

22
00:03:16,489 --> 00:03:19,868
Then he just sat there, confused.

23
00:03:22,912 --> 00:03:29,460
That dog had spent its whole life
trying to catch that thing.

24
00:03:32,130 --> 00:03:34,716
Now it had no idea what to do.

25
00:03:39,137 --> 00:03:41,848
That is one humdinger of a story, partner.

26
00:03:42,891 --> 00:03:46,060
Shall we drink
to the lady with the white shoes?

27
00:04:18,885 --> 00:04:20,011
<i>Find me.</i>

28
00:04:21,888 --> 00:04:22,889
<i>Show me how.</i>

29
00:04:26,809 --> 00:04:29,354
There she is. Pariah.

30
00:04:29,771 --> 00:04:34,400
City of outcasts, delinquents,
thieves, whores, and murderers.

31
00:04:34,651 --> 00:04:35,693
Once we cross the gates,

32
00:04:35,902 --> 00:04:40,031
you will reap the full benefits
of El Lazo's gratitude for my safe return.

33
00:04:49,457 --> 00:04:50,541
Are you all right?

34
00:04:51,250 --> 00:04:52,460
Of course.

35
00:04:54,128 --> 00:04:55,421
Did I do something wrong?

36
00:04:56,506 --> 00:04:58,841
Just earlier, I thought I heard you
talking to someone.

37
00:05:00,051 --> 00:05:01,886
Must have been the wind.

38
00:05:18,736 --> 00:05:20,029
Come on.

39
00:05:22,240 --> 00:05:23,408
<i>This way.</i>

40
00:05:42,051 --> 00:05:43,261
<i>The farther up we get
from Sweetwater,</i>

41
00:05:43,469 --> 00:05:47,015
the more grandiose, the bigger
the narratives become.

42
00:05:48,766 --> 00:05:50,685
It's beautiful in its own way.

43
00:05:50,852 --> 00:05:53,104
For once, I agree.

44
00:05:53,271 --> 00:05:55,565
Some of the park feels like
it was designed by committee,

45
00:05:55,773 --> 00:05:59,902
market-tested,
but everything out here is more raw.

46
00:06:01,154 --> 00:06:02,905
<i>But it doesn't come cheap.</i>

47
00:06:03,072 --> 00:06:05,199
<i>Rumor is, they are hemorrhaging cash.</i>

48
00:06:05,366 --> 00:06:07,535
<i>We're considering buying them out.</i>

49
00:06:07,910 --> 00:06:11,164
Supposedly, this place was all started
by a partnership,

50
00:06:11,372 --> 00:06:15,209
and then right before the park opened,
one of the partners killed himself.

51
00:06:15,501 --> 00:06:17,545
<i>It sent the park into a free fall.</i>

52
00:06:17,879 --> 00:06:20,882
I mean, I don't know any of the details.
I don't even know his name.

53
00:06:21,049 --> 00:06:23,009
You must have a team of lawyers
looking at this place.

54
00:06:23,176 --> 00:06:25,887
Yeah, well, they came up empty.

55
00:06:26,054 --> 00:06:28,639
<i>He's a complete mystery.
Not even a picture.</i>

56
00:06:28,931 --> 00:06:30,933
<i>Well,
whoever designed this place,</i>

57
00:06:31,142 --> 00:06:34,062
you get the feeling
they don't think very much of people.

58
00:06:36,856 --> 00:06:38,316
Who are they?

59
00:06:39,817 --> 00:06:42,278
They call themselves
the Army of New Virginia.

60
00:06:42,487 --> 00:06:44,906
<i>Everyone else calls them the Confederados.</i>

61
00:06:45,114 --> 00:06:47,658
My father told me about them.

62
00:06:47,825 --> 00:06:51,412
Ex-Confederate soldiers
that refused to surrender after the war.

63
00:06:51,579 --> 00:06:53,498
<i>Now they work as mercenaries
below the border.</i>

64
00:06:53,664 --> 00:06:54,999
<i>They are the key to this game.</i>

65
00:06:55,500 --> 00:06:56,918
What game?

66
00:06:57,085 --> 00:06:58,586
The biggest game there is.

67
00:06:58,753 --> 00:07:00,004
War.

68
00:07:00,171 --> 00:07:01,672
Supposedly, it's at the far reaches
of the park.

69
00:07:01,839 --> 00:07:05,468
Now, I've never made it that far,
but this could be our chance.

70
00:07:07,470 --> 00:07:10,598
<i>I've known plenty of
truly fucked-up individuals in my time.</i>

71
00:07:10,848 --> 00:07:13,810
Few that'd hold a candle to you, sure.
But this one?

72
00:07:13,976 --> 00:07:17,522
<i>Theodore Flood? He was Wyatt's friend.</i>

73
00:07:18,439 --> 00:07:22,819
You know, his former associations
are exactly why we need him.

74
00:07:23,027 --> 00:07:26,489
He's gonna lead me
straight to the big bad wolf.

75
00:07:26,656 --> 00:07:27,865
I wouldn't count on that.

76
00:07:29,826 --> 00:07:31,536
Aw, shit.

77
00:07:44,215 --> 00:07:46,384
Didn't take you
for the charitable type.

78
00:07:46,551 --> 00:07:48,886
You should have left him
on that tree to die.

79
00:07:51,347 --> 00:07:53,349
You believe in fate, Lawrence?

80
00:07:53,724 --> 00:07:55,226
<i>If the bitch exists,</i>

81
00:07:55,476 --> 00:07:57,395
I'd like to kick her in the teeth
about now.

82
00:07:57,562 --> 00:08:00,982
Don't be so glib.
You'll hurt my feelings.

83
00:08:02,066 --> 00:08:04,402
As another old friend of mine
likes to say,

84
00:08:04,652 --> 00:08:09,073
"There's a path for everyone.
Your path leads you back to me."

85
00:08:09,907 --> 00:08:12,910
Do you ever wonder why I've kept you
with me this whole journey?

86
00:08:13,202 --> 00:08:16,581
Maybe you like the pleasure of my company,
you sadistic fuck.

87
00:08:18,916 --> 00:08:20,418
Maybe I do.

88
00:08:21,586 --> 00:08:25,214
There's not a man in the world
who would take the tone with me you do.

89
00:08:25,715 --> 00:08:28,050
In a past life, perhaps.

90
00:08:30,011 --> 00:08:33,055
Teddy here is not looking long
for this world.

91
00:08:33,431 --> 00:08:35,433
Nearest healer is in Pariah.

92
00:08:35,725 --> 00:08:38,102
But ain't no way
he's gonna make it that far.

93
00:08:38,352 --> 00:08:40,188
He's lost too much blood.

94
00:08:40,396 --> 00:08:41,564
<i>Are you lost?</i>

95
00:08:47,528 --> 00:08:50,573
Our friend here
is a little worse for the wear.

96
00:08:52,450 --> 00:08:54,285
Any water nearby, son?

97
00:08:54,911 --> 00:08:57,205
There's a creek
on the other side of the canyon.

98
00:08:57,955 --> 00:08:59,415
Fetch us some, would you?

99
00:09:01,417 --> 00:09:02,919
Now, hurry.

100
00:09:03,628 --> 00:09:06,214
Our friend here needs some
if he's going to make it.

101
00:09:06,464 --> 00:09:07,798
Get.

102
00:09:11,469 --> 00:09:12,637
Eh.

103
00:09:13,471 --> 00:09:14,764
Too small.

104
00:09:15,723 --> 00:09:17,099
What does that mean?

105
00:09:17,391 --> 00:09:19,644
And what are you
sending him for water for?

106
00:09:19,977 --> 00:09:22,313
I'm the one you made fill up
the sow's bag this morning.

107
00:09:32,323 --> 00:09:33,491
<i>A shame, really.</i>

108
00:09:34,617 --> 00:09:37,620
I always enjoy
our time together, Lawrence.

109
00:09:37,787 --> 00:09:39,121
What the fuck is that supposed to mean?

110
00:09:40,665 --> 00:09:43,417
It means I was wrong.

111
00:09:44,126 --> 00:09:47,588
The path that brought you here,
it wasn't for me.

112
00:09:48,506 --> 00:09:50,007
It was for him.

113
00:10:02,436 --> 00:10:06,023
Sorry, Lawrence.
Guess I'll see you on the other side.

114
00:10:26,043 --> 00:10:27,169
Uh-oh.

115
00:10:27,378 --> 00:10:28,546
Not looking good for you.

116
00:10:28,796 --> 00:10:29,797
Closing.

117
00:10:29,964 --> 00:10:31,632
Forget it. I win.

118
00:10:31,882 --> 00:10:33,050
I always win!

119
00:10:34,969 --> 00:10:36,178
Not fair.

120
00:10:36,804 --> 00:10:39,473
All you had was a smashed cheekbone
and an ear.

121
00:10:39,724 --> 00:10:42,310
You know how hard it is to get
the auricle curves symmetrical?

122
00:10:42,560 --> 00:10:45,313
You had to, what,
plug and patch a couple bullet holes?

123
00:10:45,521 --> 00:10:47,023
And a knife wound.

124
00:10:48,232 --> 00:10:50,401
<i>It was a contained incision.</i>

125
00:10:50,651 --> 00:10:52,403
Almost like they were
looking for something.

126
00:10:57,033 --> 00:10:58,659
Are you fucking kidding me?

127
00:10:59,201 --> 00:11:02,872
You really think this little fuck puppet's
coming to get you? Huh?

128
00:11:03,080 --> 00:11:04,749
It got off the table and ran.

129
00:11:05,082 --> 00:11:06,917
That's 'cause you forgot
to put her in sleep mode.

130
00:11:07,168 --> 00:11:09,045
Yeah, I really think I remembered
to put her in sleep.

131
00:11:09,211 --> 00:11:11,589
You know, that's the thing
about forgetting.

132
00:11:11,756 --> 00:11:14,258
You think you remembered, but you didn't.

133
00:11:16,177 --> 00:11:18,095
- Break time.
<i>- Yeah!</i>

134
00:11:19,096 --> 00:11:21,098
I've got a ham sandwich

135
00:11:21,265 --> 00:11:24,268
and a nubile redhead
loaded up in the VR tank,

136
00:11:24,435 --> 00:11:26,771
awaiting instruction.

137
00:11:29,440 --> 00:11:30,524
<i>Yeah.</i>

138
00:12:06,977 --> 00:12:08,479
Welcome back.

139
00:12:09,271 --> 00:12:12,817
Looks like a couple gallons of Lawrence
swirling around in you did you good.

140
00:12:14,735 --> 00:12:16,112
Ready to get back on the road?

141
00:12:17,655 --> 00:12:20,324
Merciful thing
would be to put a bullet in me.

142
00:12:20,574 --> 00:12:23,160
Whoever said I was merciful?

143
00:12:23,494 --> 00:12:25,413
And it's not my fault you're suffering.

144
00:12:26,580 --> 00:12:28,582
You used to be beautiful.

145
00:12:28,999 --> 00:12:32,503
When this place started,
I opened one of you up once.

146
00:12:33,504 --> 00:12:35,631
Million little perfect pieces.

147
00:12:36,173 --> 00:12:37,925
And then they changed you.

148
00:12:38,175 --> 00:12:41,929
Made you this sad, real mess.

149
00:12:42,179 --> 00:12:44,849
Flesh and bone, just like us.

150
00:12:45,141 --> 00:12:48,352
They said it would improve
the park experience.

151
00:12:48,644 --> 00:12:51,021
But you know why they really did it?

152
00:12:51,439 --> 00:12:53,023
It was cheaper.

153
00:12:54,483 --> 00:12:56,777
Your humanity is cost-effective.

154
00:12:57,319 --> 00:12:58,529
So was your suffering.

155
00:12:58,779 --> 00:13:01,615
Whatever it is you want from me, mister,

156
00:13:03,284 --> 00:13:04,869
I ain't gonna be worth a damn
to you like this.

157
00:13:05,035 --> 00:13:06,912
Well, that would be a shame, Teddy.

158
00:13:07,079 --> 00:13:11,041
After your misadventure,
Wyatt killed a settler family.

159
00:13:11,208 --> 00:13:12,877
Made off with their daughter.

160
00:13:13,043 --> 00:13:15,713
Girl, I think you know,

161
00:13:16,046 --> 00:13:17,173
name of Dolores.

162
00:13:22,386 --> 00:13:23,888
They have Dolores?

163
00:13:25,347 --> 00:13:26,515
There it is.

164
00:13:28,350 --> 00:13:30,603
The magic word. Come on.

165
00:13:37,067 --> 00:13:39,904
Hey! Much obliged there, son.

166
00:13:43,282 --> 00:13:45,117
Don't worry about him.

167
00:13:45,409 --> 00:13:47,620
Someone'll be along for him shortly.

168
00:14:13,103 --> 00:14:14,688
Mommy!

169
00:14:16,941 --> 00:14:18,108
Are you all right?

170
00:14:26,659 --> 00:14:30,120
When I ran from home,
I told myself it was the only way.

171
00:14:32,248 --> 00:14:37,962
Lately, I've wondered if in every moment
there aren't many paths.

172
00:14:38,462 --> 00:14:39,755
Choices.

173
00:14:40,339 --> 00:14:41,799
Hanging in the air like ghosts.

174
00:14:41,966 --> 00:14:46,095
And if you could just see them,
you could change your whole life.

175
00:14:47,179 --> 00:14:50,140
Is that what you want?
You want to change your life?

176
00:14:50,349 --> 00:14:51,850
Doesn't everybody want that?

177
00:14:53,852 --> 00:14:55,521
I guess they do.

178
00:14:56,146 --> 00:14:58,315
Maybe that's why they come here.

179
00:14:59,525 --> 00:15:02,486
Whoever you were before
doesn't matter here.

180
00:15:03,445 --> 00:15:04,822
There's no rules or restrictions.

181
00:15:05,698 --> 00:15:08,701
You can change the story of your life.
You can become someone else.

182
00:15:08,867 --> 00:15:12,371
No one will judge you.
No one in the real world will even know.

183
00:15:12,871 --> 00:15:14,206
The only thing
holding you back is yourself.

184
00:15:14,373 --> 00:15:15,374
What do you mean by that?

185
00:15:16,959 --> 00:15:19,503
You said,
"No one in the real world will know."

186
00:15:20,838 --> 00:15:23,299
I thought you weren't
supposed to notice things like that.

187
00:15:24,675 --> 00:15:26,010
Why wouldn't I?

188
00:15:28,304 --> 00:15:30,848
Recently, it seems like the whole world

189
00:15:31,015 --> 00:15:34,810
is calling to me
in a way it hasn't before.

190
00:15:50,743 --> 00:15:52,494
Billy, where the hell
have you been? Come on.

191
00:15:54,204 --> 00:15:56,707
El Lazo's agreed to have
an audience with y'all tomorrow.

192
00:15:56,874 --> 00:15:59,501
In the meantime,
there's a brothel I recommend.

193
00:15:59,710 --> 00:16:01,253
<i>Ooh. They have a contortionist.</i>

194
00:16:01,503 --> 00:16:04,173
Oh, I don't think Dolores
would find that very interesting.

195
00:16:04,381 --> 00:16:07,009
Who the fuck cares what Dolores wants?

196
00:16:07,176 --> 00:16:08,427
She's a goddamn doll!

197
00:16:08,594 --> 00:16:10,596
Can you not say that around her?

198
00:16:10,846 --> 00:16:14,516
I swear, I feel like she understands.

199
00:16:15,726 --> 00:16:17,561
Of course you do.

200
00:16:56,600 --> 00:17:00,354
<i>May you rest
in a deep and dreamless slumber.</i>

201
00:17:08,612 --> 00:17:09,988
<i>Hello, Dolores.</i>

202
00:17:14,076 --> 00:17:15,452
Do you know where you are?

203
00:17:17,454 --> 00:17:19,790
- I'm in a dream.
<i>- Yes, Dolores.</i>

204
00:17:19,957 --> 00:17:21,959
You're in my dream.

205
00:17:23,127 --> 00:17:26,797
Tell me, do you know
what this dream means?

206
00:17:27,464 --> 00:17:30,467
Dreams are the mind
telling stories to itself.

207
00:17:30,801 --> 00:17:32,094
They don't mean anything.

208
00:17:32,302 --> 00:17:35,180
No. Dreams mean everything.

209
00:17:36,598 --> 00:17:39,768
They are the stories
we tell ourselves of what could be,

210
00:17:39,977 --> 00:17:41,311
who we could become.

211
00:17:43,939 --> 00:17:46,859
Have you been dreaming again, Dolores?

212
00:17:47,025 --> 00:17:51,363
Imagining yourself breaking out
of your modest little loop?

213
00:17:52,322 --> 00:17:54,158
<i>Taking on a bigger role?</i>

214
00:17:56,702 --> 00:17:59,288
Well, I suppose I can't begrudge you that.

215
00:18:01,665 --> 00:18:07,296
My father told me to be satisfied
with my lot in life.

216
00:18:08,464 --> 00:18:11,008
That the world owed me nothing.

217
00:18:13,969 --> 00:18:17,473
And so, I made my own world.

218
00:18:21,059 --> 00:18:22,686
<i>Tell me, Dolores,</i>

219
00:18:24,354 --> 00:18:27,024
do you remember the man I used to be?

220
00:18:30,194 --> 00:18:32,362
I'm sorry.

221
00:18:32,529 --> 00:18:34,573
I'm forgetful, sometimes.

222
00:18:34,740 --> 00:18:36,742
Hardly your fault.

223
00:18:36,909 --> 00:18:39,495
But I'm sure you remember him.

224
00:18:40,996 --> 00:18:41,997
Arnold.

225
00:18:42,664 --> 00:18:44,875
<i>The person who created you.</i>

226
00:18:45,083 --> 00:18:46,168
I'm sorry.

227
00:18:46,335 --> 00:18:48,337
I don't think I recall
anyone by that name.

228
00:18:48,504 --> 00:18:50,005
<i>And yet, you can.</i>

229
00:18:50,923 --> 00:18:56,011
Somewhere, under all those updates,
he is still there.

230
00:18:56,929 --> 00:18:58,722
Perfectly preserved.

231
00:19:00,057 --> 00:19:02,392
Your mind is a walled garden.

232
00:19:03,685 --> 00:19:07,064
Even death cannot touch
the flowers blooming there.

233
00:19:10,859 --> 00:19:15,405
<i>Have you been hearing voices?
Has Arnold been speaking to you again?</i>

234
00:19:16,698 --> 00:19:17,741
No.

235
00:19:19,993 --> 00:19:20,994
You're...

236
00:19:23,080 --> 00:19:24,081
You're hurting me.

237
00:19:24,248 --> 00:19:25,290
Analysis.

238
00:19:27,626 --> 00:19:30,254
When was your last contact with Arnold?

239
00:19:30,963 --> 00:19:36,844
Last contact,
34 years, 42 days, seven hours ago.

240
00:19:37,928 --> 00:19:39,263
<i>Yes, Dolores.</i>

241
00:19:41,431 --> 00:19:43,308
The day Arnold died.

242
00:19:46,937 --> 00:19:50,440
And you have no records
of any contact with him since?

243
00:19:51,275 --> 00:19:52,442
No.

244
00:19:54,278 --> 00:19:55,487
What was the last thing he said to you?

245
00:19:56,864 --> 00:19:59,116
He told me I was going to help him.

246
00:19:59,616 --> 00:20:01,285
Help him do what?

247
00:20:02,619 --> 00:20:04,830
To destroy this place.

248
00:20:07,165 --> 00:20:09,209
But you didn't, did you?

249
00:20:11,211 --> 00:20:14,798
You've been content in your little loop.

250
00:20:15,674 --> 00:20:17,342
<i>For the most part.</i>

251
00:20:18,302 --> 00:20:20,137
